                  "__cdata": "<p class=\"p_20 black\">Correct!</p><p>Correct answer is D : Anal fissure<br/>What is an anal fissure?<br />\nAn anal fissure is a split or tear in the lining of the anus, causes bleeding and burning pain after bowel movements. The usual cause is passing a very hard stool. The pain is caused by a spasm of the sphincter muscle. This happens as a protective measure by the body as stool passes through the anal canal and expands the tear. Bleeding is caused by trauma to the existing tear.<br />\n<br />\nFissures may be mistaken for and misdiagnosed as hemorrhoids. Fissures often improve by themselves, but if they don't, an ointment or medication applied directly to the fissure to relax the muscle can relieve the pain. Surgery may be needed for a chronic or recurrent (returning) fissure or if excessive sphincter spasms prevent the tear from healing on its own. Chronic anal fissures are those that do not heal within three months.<br />\n<br><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/symptoms/14612-rectal-bleeding/possible-causes\">https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/symptoms/14612-rectal-bleeding/possible-causes</a>.</p>"
